Little muscle twitches; felt muscle twitches really deep in his abdomen, almost like in the intestines; Low grade fever; Muscle soreness; Muscle tiredness; Hands were a little shaky; Very diaphoretic; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable other Nurse. This 44-year-old Nurse (Patient) reported that he received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: unknown) at single dose for vaccination in Jan2021 around 9:45am. Relevant medical history included ongoing Mild shrimp allergy  and ongoing Hypertension. Relevant concomitant drugs included amlodipine at 10 mg once daily for Hypertension since Feb2020 and ongoing. Prior Vaccinations (within 4 weeks): None.  Family Medical History Relevant to AE(s) was None. The patient was administered the COVID Vaccine around 9:45am; about 10 minutes later he had onset of little muscle twitches on the left side of his body that started in the calf then the glute, then the quadricep, then the bicep and then just started bouncing around everywhere on left side. Approximately a half an hour after that those little muscle twitches started on the right side of his body. Now the little muscle twitches are just everywhere; his hand, his heel, right now as he is speaking he is having the little muscle twitches in his heel; This event has been ongoing since onset; but changed today around 5:00am when he felt muscle twitches really deep in his abdomen, almost like in the intestines which is probably impossible, but it feels like it is not just muscular now, like it is happening in his intestines which concerns him. The little muscle twitches do not hurt, he thinks that is probably why he has waited a week to call; but the fact that they are ongoing and changed today, worsened is unsettling. He reported since that first dose of COVID Vaccine was administered he has also had low grade fever; muscle soreness; muscle tiredness. He reported that a rapid response team was called immediately because of the initial reaction he had. Later that day his hands were a little shaky, he got very diaphoretic and the nurses on the unit of the hospital said he almost fell which he does not recall at all; in response to those events he was taken to the emergency department where they did a complete workup including labs: Complete Blood Count (CBC), Comprehensive Metabolic Panel (CMP), checked his heart and everything was fine; no notable results from any of those tests. The patient was not admitted to the hospital; under observation in emergency room only. Outcome of events Little muscle twitches, Low grade fever, Muscle soreness and Muscle soreness was not resolved, outcome of other events was unknown.    Information about lot/batch number has been requested.

Rotavirus associated acute gastroenteritis; Vomiting; Prolonged vaccine virus shedding; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of rotaviral gastroenteritis in a infant patient who received Rota (Rotarix liquid formulation) for prophylaxis.  Concurrent medical conditions included combined immunodeficiency.   On an unknown date, the patient received Rotarix liquid formulation (oral). On an unknown date, less than 5 months after receiving Rotarix liquid formulation, the patient experienced rotaviral gastroenteritis (serious criteria GSK medically significant), vomiting and vaccine virus shedding. On an unknown date, the outcome of the rotaviral gastroenteritis, vomiting and vaccine virus shedding were unknown.   The reporter considered the rotaviral gastroenteritis, vomiting and vaccine virus shedding to be related to Rotarix liquid formulation.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of rotavirus associated acute gastroenteritis (AGE) and prolonged vaccine virus shedding in a patient aged between 2 months and 6-month-old of unspecified gender who was vaccinated with Rotarix (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis.  The patient was a part of longitudinal, prospective cohort study of children undergoing allogenic hematopoietic cell transplant (HCT) at 4 hospitals to better understand the epidemiology and etiologies of acute gastroenteritis (AGE) in pediatric HCT patients in the early post-HCT period from March 2015 through May 2016. [In this study, 31 patients were enrolled out of which:18 were male; 15 had matched, 8 had mismatched and 8 had haploidetical; 8 had cord blood as cell source, 9 had apheresed stem cell, 14 had bone marrow and 16 had receipt of intravenous immune globulin; 14 had re-admission in first 100 days, 50 had days post-hematopoetic cell transplant, 2 had re-admission for AGE, 16 had total body irradiation received]. No information on patient's family history or concomitant medication was provided.  On unspecified date at the age of 2 months, the patient received 1 dose of Rotarix (batch number not provided). On an unspecified date, after vaccination, the patient was diagnosed with severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID).  On an unknown date from March 2015 through May 2016, an unknown period after vaccination, before HCT or on the day of HCT, the patient's stool sample was collected. The sample was found positive for rotavirus by RT-PCR. No AGE symptoms were reported at that time. Almost at the age of 6 months, the patient was admitted to the hospital underwent allogenic HCT. 1 and 2-week post-HCT, the patient had diarrhea and vomiting. The patient's stool sample was collected 2-week post-HCT and tested by RT-PCR. The patient was found positive for rotavirus. The patient was diagnosed with rotavirus associated-AGE. [In this study, AGE was defined as unexplained diarrhea more than equal to 3 episodes in a 24-hour period and/or unexplained (i.e. not related to medication, mucositis, or other identifiable cause) vomiting more than equal to 1 episode in a 24-hour period. In patients with chronic vomiting and diarrhea, an unexplained doubling of the number of episodes of vomiting or diarrhea was considered consistent with AGE. The end of an AGE episode was defined as the return to stooling or emesis pattern prior to episode]. Rotavirus vaccine virus strain was confirmed in the sample by genotyping. The patient reported no AGE symptoms 3-week post-HCT. 4 and 5-week post-HCT, the patient reported diarrhea and vomiting. The patient's stool sample was collected 5-week post-HCT and tested by RT-PCR. The sample was positive for Rotarix vaccine virus strain. The patient reported no AGE symptoms 6-week post-HCT. 7 and 8-week post-HCT, the patient reported diarrhea and vomiting. The patient's stool sample was not collected at that time. The patient reported no AGE symptoms 9-week post-HCT. 10, 11 and 12-week post-HCT, the patient reported no AGE symptoms. The patient's stool sample was collected after each week respectively. The samples were found positive for Rotarix vaccine virus strain. 13 and 14-week post-HCT, the patient reported no AGE symptoms and no stool sample was collected at that time. The patient received broad-spectrum antimicrobials, including a parenterally administered beta-lactam agent with anti-Pseudomonal coverage during the study. [In this study, 16 patients received intravenous immune globulin (IVIG) during the study. 5 patients who received IVIG had a pathogen detected compared with 8 patients who did not receive IVIG. 7 patients with pathogen detections developed gut GVHD compared with 9 patients without pathogen detection. 11 patients with pathogen detection developed any GVHD compared with 12 of those without pathogen detection].  The author did not comment on the relationship between the event of rotavirus associated acute gastroenteritis (AGE) and Rotarix. The authors concluded "In summary, our prospective, multicenter, longitudinal cohort of transplant recipients highlights the importance of testing for a wide range of enteric pathogens and corroborates previous data that show that prolonged shedding of viral pathogens can occur in immunocompromised hosts. Our data also emphasize that subsequent detections of the same pathogen may represent new infection, as noted in the patient with 2 adenovirus types. In this HCT cohort, infection was self-limited and not associated with high morbidity. Our findings reinforce the recognized challenges in interpreting C. difficile test-positive results in high-risk hosts with, and without, associated symptomatology. Despite the small nature of this pilot study, these data will inform further design and direction of AGE studies that can more precisely assess the etiology of AGE in this vulnerable population." This article is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restriction.      Lab Comments: On an unknown date from March 2015 through May 2016, an unknown period after vaccination, before HCT or on the day of HCT, the patient's stool sample was collected. The sample was found positive for rotavirus by RT-PCR. The patient's stool sample was collected 2-week post-HCT and tested by RT-PCR. The patient was found positive for rotavirus. The patient was diagnosed with rotavirus associated-AGE. Rotavirus vaccine virus strain was confirmed in the sample by genotyping. The patient's stool sample was collected 5-week post-HCT and tested by RT-PCR. The sample was positive for Rotarix vaccine virus strain.  The patient's stool sample was collected after 9, 10, 11, 12 week post-HCT . The samples were found positive for Rotarix vaccine virus strain

Patient received her COVID-19 booster (Pfizer/BioNTech) at the Health Department on 12/20/2021 at 1:15 pm per father.  She started to have flu-like symptoms that evening at 11:00 pm- fever, achy and sore arm.  She took Ibuprofen 600mg at 11:00 pm and went to bed.  She awoke on 12/21/2021 feeling the same symptoms and took Tylenol 500mg at 8:00 am.  She attended Gymnastics practice from 9:00 am  to 1:00pm and continued with feverish feeling, achiness and sore arm.  She took Ibuprofen 600mg at 1:00 pm.  She started with sharp Right Lower Quadrant abdominal pain at 5:00pm that evening and they continued to rotate Tylenol and ibuprofen for pain/symptom control through the night and next day.  They contacted the pcp via test and office (PA-C) at 8:42 am and 9:21 am on 12/22/2021 with list of symptoms and asked for recommendations - at that point pain was moderate (5 out of 10)  but not worsened with movement, low grade temperature 100-101 believed to be due to recent vaccine.  Pain and fever improved some with over the counter pain relievers (Tylenol at 10:00 am).  Denied nausea, vomiting, diarrhea.  Had normal appetite and BM.  Parents concerned maybe just gas pain.  PCP voiced concern for possible appendicitis and what to watch for and when to go to ED.  Checked in via text at 4:51 pl and no change.  Stable and resting but increased pain now with pressing in RLQ (8 out of 10), afebrile.  PCP recommends ER evaluation.  Patient is taken to ER by father and CT of abdomen and pelvis revealed mildly dilated appendix and fluid-filled measuring up to 9mm, also with some diffuse enhancement of the mucosa minimal infiltrative changes seen around the appendix which could represent appendicitis.   labs were normal including normal white count.  Surgical consult recommended IV dose of cefotetan, rx for Augmentin and discharge home with plan to surgically remove appendix tomorrow since she was stable.  Appendectomy occurred on 12/23/2021 at 4:30pm.  Patient did well with procedure and is recovering as expected.

Initial report received from a consumer's parent on 05 November 2010. A 17-year-old female patient received on 04 October 2010 a left deltoid intramuscular (IM) injection of MENACTRA, lot number U3356BA and a right deltoid IM injection of FLUVIRIN, manufacturer Novartis lot number UH180AC. The patient's medical history was not reported but the patient was taking multiple vitamins. She had no adverse events following prior vaccinations and she had no vaccinations within 4 weeks prior to receiving MENACTRA and FLUVIRIN. On 29 October 2010, the patient developed a fever of 103. The next day on 30 October 2010, she developed a loss of feeling/sensation in her mouth and was not able to taste. By Saturday 30 October 2010, the fever cleared. The loss of sensation progressed to the arms, hands and fingers. By Tuesday 02 November 2010, the patient's legs and feet became affected. The patient could walk and had control over movement but the sensation was dulled. She could not feel her extremities. The patient's range of motion (ROM) was normal. The patient was seen by a doctor and had blood work which included sedimentation rate (sed rate), complete blood count with differential (CBC with diff), metabolic, "THS", and vitamin B12. The results of the testing were not reported. The outcome was reported as not recovered. Documents held by sender: None.

At 0900 this morning my face next to the right side of my mouth started itching. I immediately felt it swell. I looked in the mirror and could see the left lower part of my face (lower cheek by the edge of my mouth) swell and my right upper lip started to swell. I took a Benadryl (25mg oral tablet) and my roommate drove me to the Emergency Room. That area of my face continued to swell and impacted my lower lip as well. My lips were numb and tingling and I could feel my cheek swell more inside my mouth as it was touching my teeth. I was monitored (vital signs and pulse ox) for 90 minutes and received 20 mg of pepcid oral tablet and 10 mg dexamethasone oral tablet- both 1x only.

About 12-13 minutes into my wait after getting the vaccination... my throat had a tickle in it... like I needed to clear my throat.  So I did... and then again.... and again.    Then I felt dizzy and disoriented... foggy headed kind of drunk feeling.    Then within what seemed like seconds... my mouth felt full so I opened my mouth and looked in the mirror.   My tongue seemed bigger than usual and lighter in color.  But what was most noticeable was that I had Ripples along the whole outer edge and side of my tongue.    pulse ox reading was an 89 so they administered a prescription strength Benadryl shot and told me they would need to monitor me and keep an eye on me.  Another woman drove me from the vaccination site to the clinic where they checked my oxygen levels again and i was already back up to 99.  They monitored me and checked on me for about 15-20 minutes before releasing me.  My tongue finally felt normal again about 2 hours later while resting at home.

It was reported in a published article, that a thin 59-year-old woman presented to the emergency department with a 3-day history of severe pain and decreased mobility of her left shoulder after receiving PNEUMOVAX 23 vaccine injection in the left deltoid approximately 2 hours prior to the onset of symptoms. Just before presenting to the emergency department, she noted swelling and redness of the soft tissue overlying the anterior aspect of her shoulder and an elevated temperature of 99.9F. Ten years prior she had received a deltoid PNEUMOVAX 23 vaccine with no adverse reaction. Information regarding which arm was injected in the previous vaccination was not available. Her medical history was significant for asthma. On examination, she had a temperature of 97.7F, left anterior shoulder swelling, erythema, and warmth to touch, with subcutaneous swelling and erythema extending anteriorly from the shoulder to the ante-cubital fossa. She had significant pain with minimal shoulder motion in any plane. The orthopedic department was consulted for evaluation of possible septic arthritis of the glenohumeral joint. Laboratory data showed a peripheral blood white blood cell count of 10, C-reactive protein of 18.1 and erythrocyte sedimentation rate of 51. The glenohumeral joint was aspirated in the emergency department, producing a small amount of fluid that was bloody with no obvious purulence. The fluid showed a white blood cell count of 12,125 with 84% polymorphonuclear leukocytes; the Gram stain was negative. Based on the clinical presentation and laboratory data the orthopedic department admitted the patient for further evaluation of a possible septic arthritis. Multisequence magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the left shoulder was performed with and without contrast the MRI findings were consistent with a full-thickness tear of the anterior supraspinatus tendon with 1.2 cm proximal retraction, fluid in the subacromial/subdeltoid bursa (also reported as MRI of the affected shoulder with and without contrast showed only a partial thickness tear of the rotator cuff), and a small amount of subcutaneous edema with no evidence of abscess formation. After the results were reviewed, the patient underwent arthroscopic irrigation and debridement of her left shoulder. Antibiotics were held until intraoperative cultures were obtained. Substantial inflammation was noted throughout the shoulder with no evidence of purulent material. The articular cartilage did not appear damaged. The biceps tendon was intact and appeared normal. A small partial-thickness tear involving the anterior aspect of the rotator cuff was present, with no evidence of a full-thickness tear. Some of the friable inflammatory tissue was collected for culture. Total irrigation amounted to 4.5 L of normal saline. She was prescribed 1g of cefazolin intravenously every 8 hours. Postoperative, she improved clinically in regard to her pain level and range of motion (ROM) of the shoulder. She remained afebrile, and all cultures remained negative. After 72 hours, antibiotics were discontinued and she was discharged. She was seen at 2, 6, and 12 weeks postoperatively, with ROM improving with physical therapy at each visit. She was released from follow-up at 12 weeks, with ROM nearly equal to the contralateral shoulder. The patient had a mixed laboratory picture with normal white blood cell and elevated C-reactive protein and erythrocyte sedimentation rate. Her joint fluid cell count and Gram stain were not indicative of septic arthritis, but her clinical presentation was suspicious. Given her clinical presentation, it was felt that the potential risk of articular cartilage damage from possible septic arthritis necessitated an arthroscopic irrigation and debridement. After a discussion with the patient regarding the risks and benefit of surgery, she elected to proceed with surgery. In reporting the case of pseudoseptic arthritis following PNEUMOVAX 23, the author hypothesized that, due to its multivalent composition PNEUMOVAX 23 might be capable of inducing a more prominent inflammatory response. In this case, the authors suspected that the vaccination was inadvertently injected into the glenohumeral joint directly through the rotator cuff, given the lack of a full-thickness tear and patient's thin body habitus. This could account for severe aseptic inflammation of the joint space with onset of symptoms soon after vaccine administration, as observed in both cases. This case further illustrates the fact that caution should be taken when injecting a vaccination in the area of the upper deltoid. Additional information has been requested.

Corneal Allograft Rejection; blurring of vision in the left eye; conjunctiva had trace injection; cornea had temporal stromal and epithelial edema; 1+ cells in the anterior chamber; Eye inflammation; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of transplant rejection in a elderly female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included fuchs' endothelial dystrophy (undergone Descemet stripping endothelial keratoplasty in 2010 in OD and in 2009 in OS). Previously administered products included influenza vaccine. Concomitant products included Herpes zoster (Shingrix) and Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2019-2020 season).   In September 2020, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season. On an unknown date, 6 weeks after receiving Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season, the patient experienced transplant rejection (serious criteria GSK medically significant), blurred vision, conjunctival injection, corneal edema, anterior chamber cell and eye inflammation. The patient was treated with loteprednol and prednisolone acetate. On an unknown date, the outcome of the transplant rejection, blurred vision, conjunctival injection and anterior chamber cell were unknown and the outcome of the corneal edema was recovered/resolved and the outcome of the eye inflammation was recovering/resolving.   The reporter considered the transplant rejection, blurred vision, conjunctival injection, corneal edema, anterior chamber cell and eye inflammation to be possibly related to Shingrix. It was unknown if the reporter considered the transplant rejection, blurred vision, conjunctival injection, corneal edema, anterior chamber cell and eye inflammation to be related to Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Zoster subunit vaccine (RZV)-associated corneal allograft rejection, in a female patient of unspecified age, who was vaccinated with Shingrix (GlaxoSmithKline) and Unspecified Infleunza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to Table 1 reported in this literature article. This case corresponds to a case reported in this literature article.  The patient was a healthy woman. The patient had undergone Descemet stripping endothelial keratoplasty in 2010 in the OD and in 2009 in the OS for Fuchs endothelial dystrophy. In 2019 (one year prior to presentation), the grafts were clear and best corrected visual acuity was 20/20 OD and 20/25 OS. The patient did not have previous history of viral keratitis or an episode of herpes zoster of any dermatome. No information on patient family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported.  In August 2020, the patient was vaccinated with first dose of Shingrix (administration route and site unknown; batch number not provided), and the second dose of Shingrix in September 2020, along with the influenza vaccine (administration route and site unknown; batch number not provided for both). The age at vaccination was not reported but it could be between 68 or 69 years at the time of vaccination. In previous years, the patient had received the influenza vaccine each fall without incident.  On an unknown date in 2020, 6 weeks after the second dose of Shingrix vaccination, the patient had blurring of vision in the left eye. At the time of onset of symptoms, the patient had been using topical loteprednol 0.5%, 1 drop 1 to 2 times per week in both eyes. At the age of 69 years, in October 2020, the patient presented with a 1-week history of blurring of vision in the left eye. At the time of the visit, visual acuity OS was 20/70. The conjunctiva had trace injection. The cornea had temporal stromal and epithelial edema, with 1+ cells in the anterior chamber. Intraocular pressure was 13 mm Hg. The patient denied systemic or local infection or trauma. The patient was diagnosed with allograft rejection. The patient was treated with prednisolone acetate 1% 8 times per day. Within 3 weeks, the anterior chamber was quiet, and after 8 weeks, the corneal edema had resolved. Vision at 3 months was 20/25 with no residual edema. Improvement of inflammation occurred quickly after intense topical steroid therapy.  The author commented "It elicits a robust immune response, with both humoral and cell-mediated responses detectable 1 month after the first dose. RZV is more immunogenic than the older ZVL. It is likely that RZV may pose a greater risk for associated immune-mediated reactions, such as reactivation of zoster keratitis and corneal allograft rejection than ZVL. Identifiable potential risk factors other than the RZV were as follows: One patient had a history of a second Descemet stripping endothelial keratoplasty in the fellow eye 10 years previously. One patient had a history of 1 previous PKP that failed because of allograft rejection. The same patient also underwent removal of 1 suture before the onset of blurred vision. One drop of topical loteprednol 0.5% was administered at the time of the suture removal, and the patient was instructed to continue his previous regimen of prednisolone acetate 1% 4 per day. The third patient had 1 episode of rejection in a previous transplant. Original indications for keratoplasty were corneal endothelial dystrophy, past trauma, and keratoconus. In 2 of the 3 cases, rejection occurred despite relatively high level of topical corticosteroid therapy: difluprednate emulsion 0.05% 3 per day (for the treatment of cystoid macular edema), in 1 patient, and prednisolone acetate 1% 4 per day, in a second patient. Improvement of inflammation occurred quickly after intense topical steroid therapy in all 3 cases. Onset of symptoms of allograft rejection occurred 5 weeks after the first RZV dose in 1 patient. In the other 2 patients, blurred vision was noted 1 and 6 weeks after the second dose. It has been reported that "overall, 30% of transplanted corneas experience at least 1 episode of immune reaction."10 Therefore, observation of a chance temporal association with RZV is possible. However, with 3 cases identified within a 3-month period, it is reasonable to consider the possibility that RZV may increase the risk for corneal allograft rejection.".  The author concluded "RZV, which elicits a more robust immune reaction than the zoster live-attenuated vaccine, ZVL, may increase the risk of allograft rejection in immunocompetent patients with preexisting corneal endothelial or penetrating transplants. Based on the available data, it may be reasonable to increase the topical corticosteroid regimen before the first dose, until approximately 3 months after the second dose of ZVL".  This is 1 of the 3 valid cases reported in this literature article.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2021GSK167260:Same reporter

There were no other complications or abnormalities. The baby's experience has been captured in WAES # 1001USA00985B1. I visited my PCP on  04/02/2021 and she advised to see her again if the symptoms did not continue to resolve on their own. stiff neck/other side of her neck was stiff; face started tingling; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable Nurse (patient). A 58-year-old female patient received first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, solution for injection, lot number EK5130, expiry date unknown) via unspecified route of administration at left deltoid on 22Dec2020 at single use for COVID-19 immunization. Medical history included true nut allergies (has an epi pen at home), migraines (used Imitrex injections), menopause. The patient got the COVID-19 vaccination this morning 22Dec2020. They said to wait 10 minutes then she could leave. She felt fine. As she was leaving on 22Dec2020, employee services was far away from where she parked, she was almost to the parking lot and started feeling like she had a stiff neck. She thought she slept wrong, she did not think it was related. Then the other side of her neck was stiff. So she was waiting in her car and did not drive away in case she needed to go back inside. Then her face started tingling. It came on gradual and lasted 4-5 minutes and then it went away. She was fine now. She was at home. She feels fine, she was not short of breath. She did have an epi pen at home due to true nut allergies, but she has no concern over potential respiratory problems or anything like that. In the past she had migraines, and she would use Imitrex injections. Right before it would make her migraine go away, she would feel a muscle spasm in her neck and it would release and her headache would go away. She would compare her symptoms to that. She has not had an Imitrex injection in years. Her headaches went away after menopause and she has not needed them. Her primary care did not administer the vaccination. She received it at the hospital where she worked. She was wondering, should she get the second dose of vaccination. Again, she was not at all concerned, she had felt this similar feeling before, but the face tingling was new. She thought this should be reported as this was a brand new vaccine. The outcome of the events stiff neck/other side of her neck was stiff, face started tingling was recovered on 22Dec2020. The reporter considered the events non-serious and face started tingling related.

Got the DTaP and Heb B shots around 10:00 AM, son had a mild cold with no fever. Later in the afternoon to early evening my son was very irritable and felt slightly warm. I gave him Tylenol around 5 pm. We went to bed around 8 pm. I woke around 2 am because my son's body was so hot it woke me up. Our thermometer is very unreliable but he got more Tylenol and husband went to store for a new thermometer. About 1 hour after Tylenol his temperature was 101. In the morning my son was not his usual happy self. He usually greets anyone (especially cashiers) with a giant smile. Instead he just stared lethargically. He was very irritable and clingy all day. Fever present at all times, temp depended on how recently he got Tylenol or Motrin and how much he managed to spit out. It is now 6:30 am on 12/18/2014 and he's puked a tiny bit this morning, still has a raging fever and is absolutely miserable. He cries any time we aren't laying down in bed together, with my breast out and available to him if he needs to nurse and/or cuddle.

patient passed out less than 5 minutes after receiving the moderna booster vaccine (0.25mL) and the influenza vaccine (flulaval quadrivalent). He had received the first two moderna shots in the past and had no issues. They were both administered in the left deltoid muscle. After I administered both vaccines a couple minutes later, the patient lost all color in face and began to seize (no history of seizures in the past). His arms began to shake, he made a loud moan, and starting moving his head around. Patient was sitting in a chair at the time and so I lowered him slowly and safely to the floor and laid him on his left side supporting his head. He lost consciousness for about 30 seconds (thats how long the seizure lasted) and afterwards regained consciousness. Was alert and able to answer questions correctly, but expressed that he didnt know what had occurred but that he felt disoriented. Two to three minutes went by and he began to seize again for the next 30 seconds. paramedics were called. no injury to the patient. trasnferred to the hospital to get checked out. documented accordingly in VAERS report and in patients chart. This case is a cluster of 6 patients who tested positive for pertussis following administration of Tdap. The 5 other patients are captured in case numbers 2012-01240, 2012-02345, 2012-02348, 2012-02350 and 2012-02351. Initial report was received from a health care professional on 24 February 2012. An 11-year-old male patient had received a 0.5 mL dose 5 injection of Tdap (manufacturer, lot number, route and site of administration not reported) on 05 September 2005. The patient was 4-years-old at the time. On 07 September 2005, the patient received a 0.5 mL dose 4 injection of IPV, a 0.5 mL dose 2 injection of MMR and a 0.5 mL dose 1 injection of Hep A (manufacturers, lot numbers, routes and sites not reported). The patient was seen on 09 January 2012 with complaints of cough for the last month, fits of cough, can't catch his breath, brings up mucus and a low grade fever. The patient's sister and dad have the same cough. The previous weekend the patient was vomiting with the stomach flu. Upon examination, the patient had erythema on tonsils, no cervical lymphadenopathy, good air movement with no crackles or wheezes, sandpapery feeling skin with colored papules on back. The physician's assessment was cough and pharyngitis. A rapid strep test was done and results were negative. The patient's sister tested positive for pertussis so the patient was treated for pertussis as well with azithromycin. No laboratory testing was done for the patient to confirm pertussis. The patient had no known drug allergies (NKDA) and took no concomitant medications. The patient had a past medical history of headache and unspecified disorder of male genital organs. The patient's vaccine history included 4 previous doses of TRIPEDIA (sanofi pasteur Inc): lot number U0356CA on 13 March 2001, lot number U0378AA on 25 May 2001, lot number U0532DA on 17 August 2001 and lot number U0549AA on 26 July 2002. The patient was up-to-date on HepB, Hib, IPV/OPV, PREVNAR, MMR, Varicella, HepA and Flu vaccinations. No further information was available at the time of the report. The patient's outcome was not reported. Documents held by sender: Medical records.

A male patient of an unspecified age received bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE) dose 1 on 04Mar2021 (Batch/Lot number was not reported), dose 2 on 04Apr2021 (Batch/Lot number was not reported), both at age of 58-year-old intramuscular as single dose for covid-19 immunisation; adalimumab (HUMIRA), subcutaneous from an unspecified date (Lot Number: 1142175) and ongoing, at Citrate Free for Moderate to severe rheumatoid arthritis, methotrexate sodium (METHOTREXATE SODIUM), route of administration, start and stop date, batch/lot number and dose were not reported for an unspecified indication. The patient medical history was not reported. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported.  The patient experienced gallbladder removal (medically significant) on 30Jul2021, heartburn, rheumatoid arthritis flare up, adverse drug reaction, pain in hand on unknown date.  The action taken in response to the events for bnt162b2 was not applicable, for adalimumab was dose not changed, for methotrexate sodium was permanently withdrawn on an unspecified date.  the outcome of gallbladder removal was recovered in 2021, Rheumatoid arthritis flare up, Adverse drug reaction (as reported) was not recovered , for other event was unknown. Clinical course: Solicited report by a consumer of a 59-year-old male with events of gallbladder removal and non-serious heartburn, rheumatoid arthritis flare up, had reaction to methotrexate and occasional pain in hands with Humira (Adalimumab). There was no reported medical history. On unknown dates, the patient experienced heartburn, rheumatoid arthritis flare up, had reaction to methotrexate and occasional pain in hands. On 30Jul2021 the patient experienced gallbladder removal. On an unknown date, gallbladder removal resolved. Methotrexate was also considered suspect. Patient had reaction to methotrexate which caused heartburn and had to stop the drug. It was unknown if he was enrolled in a covid-19 vaccine trial. On 04Mar2021, he received first dose covid-19 vaccine manufactured by Pfizer. On 04Apr2021, he received second dose covid-19 vaccine manufactured by Pfizer.  Causality for Humira (Adalimumab): The reporters causality for the event(s) of gallbladder removal, heartburn and had reaction to methotrexate with Humira (Adalimumab) was no reasonable possibility. The reporters causality for the event(s) of rheumatoid arthritis flare up with Humira (Adalimumab) was a reasonable possibility. The reporters causality for the event(s) of occasional pain in hands was not provided. RA opinion is that there is no reasonable possibility that the events of gallbladder removal, heartburn, rheumatoid arthritis flare up, had reaction to methotrexate and occasional pain in hands are related to Humira (Adalimumab).  The reporter's assessment of the causal relationship of the events with the suspect products bnt162b2 and methotrexate sodium was not provided at the time of this report. Since no determination has been received, the case is managed based on the company causality assessment.  No follow-up attempts are needed; information about lot/batch number cannot be obtained. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on available information and known drug profile, a possible causal relationship cannot be excluded between the suspect vaccine product bnt162b2 and the reported event rheumatoid arthritis flare up. The other events are not considered likely related to the suspect product bnt162b2. Based on available information and possible temporal association, a possible causal relationship cannot be excluded between the suspect vaccine product methotrexate sodium and the reported events heartburn and pain in hand. The event rheumatoid arthritis flare up is not considered related to the suspect product methotrexate sodium based on negative dechallenge result that the event not recovered after methotrexate sodium withdrawn. This case will be reassessed once additional information is available.

arm puffiness; her left breast was swollen; had a lot of arm aches where the injection site was; Body aches; swelling in her lymph nodes; had some nerve tingling in her finger; Arm swelling; swelling under her left side of the arm, the left armpit; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient) via medical information team. A 61-year-old female patient received second dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Formulation: Solution for injection, Lot Number: EL9264, expiry date unknown), via an unspecified route of administration in left arm on 04Feb2021 at 17:30 in the beginning of February (at the age of 61 years old) as single for COVID-19 immunization. Patient previously received first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Formulation: Solution for injection, Lot Number: EL3302), via an unspecified route of administration in left arm on 14Jan2021 in the middle of January (at the age of 61 years old) for COVID-19 immunization and experienced no reaction. Medical history included headache. No family medical history relevant to adverse events was provided. No concomitant medications were reported. Patient occasionally took Excedrin or Avil expectorant for headaches and experienced no reaction on previous exposure to drug but did not take any prescription medication. The patient did not receive any other vaccinations within four weeks prior to the first administration date of the suspect vaccine. The patient did not administer any vaccine on same date with the Pfizer vaccine considered as suspect. Patient had no problems with the first injection received on 14Jan2021; all the events started after she received the second dose of the vaccine. On 05Feb2021, patient had body aches. 14 or 15 hours after the injection, patient's arm started aching. Patient had a lot of arm aches on the injection site. Patient took Tylenol for the body aches, which lasted a few hours and recovered on 05Feb2021. Patient was having a lingering symptom. On 06Feb2021, patient's left arm, in the armpit, had puffiness, it was not sore in the tissue and she did not know if it is the muscles or tissue. Patient had swelling under her left side of the arm, the left armpit and noticed the lymph node and got scared. Her arm really hurt on the third day and it was worse than the second day. Swelling eventually went down but not completely. She said it stayed the same and she has not noticed any more improvement for the last few months. She kept thinking it would go down more but it was the same. Patient stated that no one would notice the swelling, but she noticed a protrusion when she lifted her arm up. It did not hurt it was just there. When she lifted her arm up, the left arm was noticeably different than the right armpit. Patient's left breast was also swollen with the whole site near the armpit on 06Feb2021. Swelling started to go down but it took days. Patient had some nerve tingling in her finger on the left side and maybe in her arm, which did not last long, and she figured it was from the swelling pushing on the nerves. She did not notice it that weekend, so it might have been a few days after the weekend when she received the second vaccine. Patient had a gynecologist appointment at the beginning of April and gynecologist did not seem to be concerned, he said it could be her lymph node. Patient did not feel like she needed to go see a doctor because most of the swelling had gone down and just the lingering puffiness was still there, and she kept thinking it was going to go away and it just needed a few weeks. Swelling still had not gone down and patient had given it a few months. Events did not require a visit to emergency room or physician office. No relevant tests were performed. Outcome of the events swelling in her lymph nodes was unknown while of arm puffiness was not recovered. Outcome of the events her left breast was swollen, Arm swelling and swelling under her left side of the arm, the left armpit was recovering. Events "had a lot of arm aches where the injection site was and had some nerve tingling in her finger" recovered on an unspecified date.

2.5 hours after injection I started feeling weird, clammy cold sweats, nauseous and it felt like my eyes were bulging or like an intense pressure behind my eyes, blurry eyesight, extreme headache.  I have not ever had any issues with my blood pressure only my diabetes.  It had recently been slightly elevated but controlled mostly. I knew it was high and it suddenly just came on even after not eating at that time. I proceeded to flush with alot of water and some walking to bring it down. I wasn't exactly sure of how high it got because I don't normally have to bring my tester to work with me. However as soon as I got home I tested it and even after heavy flushing and exercise my glucose level was down to 500. It has never been that high ever. I continued to flush and monitor and not eating due to nausea and headache I was taken to the hospital. At that time my glucose reading was at 400. I was given 10 units of novolog as well as 1 full bag of fluid thru an IV.  And before I was discharged it had come down to 192.  I have only had to have insulin 1 time since 2008-9. Since then my sugar is refusing to come down below 250. My vision is still not clear and I am now attempting to keep it down with 15 units of a fast acting insulin multiple times a day. I will also be starting metformin again as of tomorrow morning to also help bring it down to a more healthy level due to the possibility of another life altering stroke.

I was given the injection and immediately went to sit in the patient observation area for the required 15 minutes. I was feeling fine, made a quick phone call, and was just sitting and waiting. I started to bend down to put my head between my knees, but that's the last thought I remember before waking up lying on the floor with the pharmacist tending to me. He said I had only been unconscious for several seconds. I was completely weak and still felt generally unwell. I also sustained a bump on my forehead and a hurt nose from hitting the floor when I collapsed. I recovered enough to walk out about 30 minutes later, and rested the rest of the day since the weakness lasted through the evening. I don't know if it was related or not, but I also started my period 4 days after that, which was 5 days earlier than expected, and it lasted a full 2 weeks (my period is typically 7-9 days).

This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of uveitis in a 29-year-old female subject who was vaccinated with hepatitis B vaccine recombinant (Hepatitis B vaccine, manufacturer unspecified). Concurrent vaccination included Salmonella typhi Vi capsular polysaccharide vaccine ;manufacturer unspecified given on an unspecified date. On an unspecified date the subject received 1st dose of Hepatitis B vaccine (unknown). One day after vaccination with Hepatitis B vaccine, the subject experienced uveitis, arthralgia, erythema nodosum and fever. This case was assessed as medically serious by GSK. Relevant test results included elevated sedimentation rate. This is one of the 32 reported cases (B0662264A till B0662297A) of uveitis which occurred after hepatitis b vaccine between 1982 and 2009. It appeared that all subject's recovered, although the treatment for uveitis was not reported. The uveitis occurred in average of 3 days after vaccination in patients without other risk factors or disease that could cause uveitis. This could be consistent with immune complex deposition or nonspecific activation from vaccine adjuvants. Although there was a debate that uveitis occurs because of hepatitis B infection there was evidence that immune complex deposition diseases such as glomerulonephritis and cryoglobulinemia occurred during chronic hepatitis B infection. Furthermore it was possible the surface antigen of the vaccine and the hepatitis B antibodies of the immune response after vaccination formed immune complexes, which initiated the ocular response of uveitis.

Babbles. Document: History and Physical. Date of Admission: 24Feb2014. CHIEF COMPLAINT: Breath-holding. HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS: The patient is a 4-month male previously healthy who was brought to the emergency room by parents complaining of breath-holding spells. As per the parents he was in his usual state of health and he went for his 4-month-old visit today for immunizations and injections including a PCV 13, Hib, DTaP and IPV. He got a prophylactic dose of TYLENOL about an hour prior to the receiving of vaccinations. After returning home around four hours later he was crying continuously with pain and the parents noticed that he was holding his breath for brief periods of time for a few seconds, but one spell was longer to the point that he turned a little blue and the mother had to shake him. He was awake all the time crying. Denies any vomiting, diarrhea, any fever, anybody sick in the family or any other complaint. Denied any abnormal movement, seizures, excessive sleepiness, excessive tiredness, twitching or any other complaints. He is crying but consolable when the mother rocks him. He is drinking less of his formula. Normally he drinks 4-6 ounces every 3-4 hours but since he got his shots he is crying and not drinking his formula. REVIEW OF SYSTEMS: All other systems reviewed and are negative. PAST HISTORY: He is a full-term baby born by normal spontaneous vaginal delivery. Birth weight 3115 g, Apgar 9 and 9. Discharged within two days of life. Newborn screen is negative. All maternal labs including GBS and HIV are negative and the mother is immune to rubella. Had influenza diagnosed and was treated with TAMIFLU for five days. Denies any complications from that. Has been well since that. The reporter denies any prior hospitalizations or any surgeries. He underwent circumcision as a newborn. The reporter any allergies to food or medications. MEDICATIONS: Not on any medications at home. FAMILY HISTORY: Denies any significant health problems in the family. Denies any seizure disorders, any cardiac problems or any other problems. SOCIAL HISTORY; Lives with father, mother, 10-year-old brother, 8-year-old sister. Denies anybody being sick at home. Denies anybody smoking at home. Denies any pets. Sleeps in a cradle. Back to sleep. EMERGENCY ROOM COURSE: On presentation to the ER the patient was afebrile, was evaluated and was found to be crying a lot, minimally consolable by the mother. Was put on a cardiorespiratory monitor and we were consulted to evaluate the patient for further management. PHYSICAL EXAMINATIONS: VITAL SIGNS: On evaluation temperature 98.8 Fahrenheit, respiratory rate 36 per minute, O2 sat 98-100% on room air, pulse rate 145 per minute, blood pressure 71/35 mmHg. He is awake in the father's arms, crying but is consolable by the parents. Head atraumatic. Anterior fontanelle open and flat. Eyes PERRL. Bilateral red reflex seen. Ears: Normal tympanic membranes bilaterally. Nose: Normal mucosa. Mouth: Normal moist mucous membranes. NEUROLOGICAL: Moro symmetrical, strong suck reflex, equal movement of extremities bilaterally, deep tendon reflexes are 2+. NECK: No masses noticed. CHEST: Symmetrical chest expansion, no retractions. LUNGS: Good air entry bilaterally, clear breath sounds. HEART: S1, S2 heard. Regular rate and rhythm. No murmurs. ABDOMEN: Soft, nontender, bowel sounds are present. No organomegaly. GENITALIA: Normal external male genitalia, Tanner stage 1, circumcised, testes descended bilaterally. EXTREMITIES: Capillary refill is less than two seconds. Peripheral pulses 2+. SKIN: Erythema and induration noticed at the site of injections bilateral anterolateral aspect of the thigh. Superficial hemangioma noticed on the occipital area of the scalp. Otherwise, skin unremarkable. ASSESSMENT AND PLAN: A 4-month-old male with breath-holding spells probably secondary to pain associated with the vaccinations. The reporter discussed with the parents that considering that the patient is having breath-holding spells and one of them being for a prolonged period with cyanosis we will recommend to admit the patient for observation. The parents agreed with the plan. HISTORY OF THE PRESENT ILLNESS: This is a 4 month old admitted for observation secondary to possible apneic spells after receiving several immunizations. This was found to be not true apnea. He was afebrile, well-appearing, tolerated all intake, had normal vital signs, remained stable on the monitor overnight. PHYSICAL EXAMINATION: He, on exam was asleep and in no distress. HEENT: Anterior fontanelle, opened soft and flat. Tympanic membranes clear. CARDIAC: S1 and S2 normal, regular rate and rhythm, 2+ pulses. LUNGS: Clear and unlabored bilaterally with regular breathing and regular breathing pattern. ABDOMEN: Soft, nondistended, with active bowel sounds. SKIN: Otherwise warm and clear. NEUROLOGIC: The baby is easily arousable and otherwise appears well. DISCHARGE PLAN: the reporter discussed with dad that this is not likely related to immunizations, nor have we found any true apnea during this visit and he is otherwise a healthy baby. He will be discharged home and given reasons to return including difficulty breathing, fever, or other concerns. Appointment will be made to follow up in 48 hours. Dad verbalized understanding of a plan. MEDICATIONS CURRENT AT THE TIME OF DISCHARGE: TYLENOL liquid, 84.6 MG = 2.644 ML, Oral, Every 4 hours PRN from 24Feb2014 to 25Feb2014 for Pain or Temp >100.4 and MOTRIN, 56.4 MG = 2.82 ML, Oral Every six hours PRN for Pain if TYLENOL not effective from 24Feb2014 to 25Feb2014. Follow-up (28Mar2014): New information received from a contactable Other HCP, on behalf of physician, includes: patient age/gender/data; course of events; concomitant medications; Discharge Summary. Follow-up (23May2014): Follow-up attempts completed. No further information expected.

Initial report received on 20 June 2012 from the Investigator participating in a post-marketing observational surveillance study under the reference number M5A16. A case of Pertussis disease in a 3-year-old female subject (initials not collected) was identified by the investigator based on review of data from the Electronic Disease Surveillance (EDSS) electronic database. The subject had received 4 doses of PENTACEL; lot number C3288AA received on 24 June 2009, lot number C3363AA received on 04 September 2009, lot number C3363AA received on 27 October 2009 and lot number C3552AA received on 08 September 2010 (routes and sites of administration not reported). The subject developed cold-like symptoms and cough on 07 May 2012, approximately one year and eight months after the last dose. On 10 May 2012, the subject developed a paroxysmal cough without a whoop. The subject also experienced posttussive vomiting and sleep disturbance. Laboratory testing included positive PCR on 17 May 2012. Chest x-ray findings were negative for pneumonia. Corrective treatments consisted of azithromycin starting on  17 May 2012 for 5 days. The subject was not hospitalized. At the time of final contact on 24 May 2012, the subject's cough was still persisting. The duration of the cough was reported at that time as 17 days. Investigator causality assessment is not required as per protocol. Documents held by sender: None.

Patient came in for his first dose of the Pfizer Covid vaccine.  He received his shot in his left arm (given @ 1:20pm on 07/29/2021).  He went to our waiting area for his 15 minutes of observation.  As soon as he sat down he start to have a reaction (1:22pm 07/29/2021).  He became unconscious.  His mother was with him and alerted the vaccinator (pharmacy technician) immediately.  Technician alerted the pharmacist/pharmacy manager.  Pharmacist ran out to check on patient.  I yelled and shook the patient.  He became alert.  He was no longer unconscious at this point.  He began sweating, his eyes kept closing.  He complained of feeling nauseated and having a headache.  Pharmacist immediately called 911.  Paramedics arrived (@ 1:40pm).  They check his vitals.  BP was 80/59. Patient then alerted the paramedics that he had to use the restroom.  He has been having diarrhea for at least the past 3 days.  Paramedics took him to the restroom.  He then was asked to have a seat outside of the restroom where his vitals were done again.  They started an IV and ran an EKG (@ 1:55pm).  Paramedics brought in stretcher and were taking him to the hospital for further observation (@2:10pm).

I was thinking I was having a heart attack, it was so bad I ended up going to the ER 3 times.

Waited 30 minutes. A little dizzy. Son drove me home. Arrived home 450. 5 pm eyes and cheeks swelling throat felt like olive stuck in it I called Kaiser. Talking to them chest began stinging hurting pressure. Told to call 911. I hung up walked two blocks to urgent care.  Chest really hurting feeling dizzy face eyes swelling throat lump getting larger.  My breathing rate normal , blood pressure normal , oxygen normal.  They took me back gave me epinephrine and depo modral  shot in right buttock cheek.  After few minutes felt better chest stopped increasing in pain throat started feeling better, face still swollen. Told me good thing I walked instead of waiting for 911. Very scarey. Told to remain up for 24-48 hours give epi if needed again. Taking 180-360 mg 24 hr Allegra daily. I stayed up  36 hours drank water .  Told can not take second shot. No vaccines until I get tested for what caused allergic reaction. Today March 23 face still off and on swelling and eyes. Seems when I begin to move around swelling starts again.

I am a 68 year old male. For the second year in a row I had a flu shot about the first of October. This year I had the Fluad 20-21 Quad 0.5 ML IJG SEQI (Info from the pharmacy receipt) injection. Last year when I got the shot I was very sick with flu like symptoms in the day immediately following the injection and again approximately three weeks later. I also had the usual expected symptoms of soreness at the injection site and general tiredness. Last year the symptoms were bad enough that I had to curtail regular activities for three to four days. This year the same thing happened to both me and my wife (66 year old female). Neither of us were real sick after the shot but we were very sick for three or four days about three weeks out from the shot. I had the shot on October 5th and I have not felt well since that time. I'm concerned about either of us getting the flu shot next given the severity of the symptoms the last two year. I looked on line regarding issue but couldn't find any credible information regarding these kinds of side effects. Last year I suppose we could have just picked up a cold but this year we have been mostly limiting interactions and wearing masks so I am really concerned that this could be something to do with the vaccine. Can you provide some guidance?

Mom has mild cognitive impairment.  She is well above average for a 93 year old. I live with her and she is highly functioning.    The day of her vaccine, she seemed very tired. The next day, she was exhausted. She had a hard time doing her normal activities. No fever. It was much more challenging for her to walk. She just couldn't get moving. It seemed to stay the same. I noticed she was having a harder time doing everything. Suddenly, her comprehension seemed to change. Within a week, she went from mild cognitive deficits to full blown cognitive impairment: not knowing how to take her pills, how to wash hands, how to use her watch/fitness tracker, to not removing her bottle cap to drink water, to having a hard time communicating. I called the Pharmacist where she had the vaccine, and they told me that this was not uncommon after the vaccine. They had been getting lots of similar calls. They haven't given out any second shots yet, and were not looking forward to it after everything they've been hearing.  This is very frightening.!!!! Our Mom cannot be left alone now.  How long will this last????!!!!

She caller her father and he came to driver her home. Patient visited orthopedist specializing in the shoulder on 08-Feb-2021, had X-rays and MRI scans taken over the next few days. Doctor determined frozen shoulder developed right after the vaccine. In April, the pain had not subsided, and patient's condition had not improved. Patient took a second cortisone shot which was not helpful. Soon after, the physical therapist and the patient came to the conclusion that therapy was not working. The pain was constant, her range of motion was very limited. There was no improvement despite following doctor's treatment plan. The shoulder lumps/muscle knots are large. On 08-Jun-2021, patient was examined by a renown sports injury orthopedist. He determined that patient might need surgery. He explained that the inflammation in her shoulder area was an inflammatory reaction to the Moderna vaccine. In an effort to avoid surgery, patient was referred to a doctor of Physiatry who will be administering another cortisone shot and will be overseeing next step, possibly another round of physical therapy. Surgery for these situations was complicated and there was no guarantee of recovery. Also, patient was in perfect health before this vaccine and it is evident that she was suffering a reaction to the Moderna vaccine. Initial report was retrieved from the scientific literature on 06 September 2012. The following information is verbatim from the abstract: "Meningococci have historically caused extensive illness among members. Three successive meningococcal vaccine types were used from 1971 through 2010; overall disease incidence dropped by >90% during this period. During 2006-2010, disease incidence of 0.38 (cases per 100,000 person-years) among members was not significantly different from the incidence of 0.26 among the age-matched general population. Of the 26 cases, 5 were fatal, 15 were vaccine failures (e.g., illness in a person who had been vaccinated), and 9 were caused by Neisseria meningitidis serogroup Y. Incidences among 17- to 19-year-old were significantly higher than among comparison populations (p<0.05). No apparent change in epidemiology of meningococcal disease was observed after replacement of quadrivalent polysaccharide vaccine with conjugate vaccine in 2007. The data demonstrate that vaccination with meningococcal vaccine is effective." According to the report, the cases were confirmed by culture, PCR or both. The information included in this case concerns a 25-29-year-old female patient who had received MENACTRA (lot number, route, site and date of administration not reported) and 8 months after vaccination developed meningococcal meningitis, year reported as 2010 (Q 3). Neisseria meningitidis serogroup was determined to be serogroup C. Treatments were not reported. No further information was available at the time of report. Death was reported as "No", however the patient's outcome was not reported. The reporter for this case is the same as for cases 2012-08240, -08241, -08242, -08243, -08244, -08245, -08246, -08247, -08248, -08249, -08250, -08251, -08252, -08254, -08255, and -08256. Documents held by sender: None.

This medically confirmed literature report (initial receipt 23-Feb-2016) concerns a 60-year old female patient who developed acute-onset massive proteinuria with NS (nephrotic syndrome) and severe AKI (acute kidney injury) soon after receiving the 2009 H1N1 influenza vaccine. The patient had medical history of bronchial asthma and there was no history of drug allergy. Her medications included montelukast, salbutamol and SERETIDE. She denied use of any other medications, including non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and herbal medications. There was no history of diabetes, hypertension, hepatitis or blood transfusion. She denied smoking, alcohol or intravenous drug use. She was referred to the emergency room (ER) by her primary medical doctor (PMD) for evaluation of elevated serum creatinine level (10.3 mg/ dL). The patient was seen by her PMD one day before her ER visit for evaluation of worsening bilateral lower extremity edema. She had received the 2009 H1N1 influenza vaccine two weeks before her ER presentation. The patient developed fever, intermittent nausea and vomiting and lower extremity edema soon after being immunized with the influenza vaccine. She had refused influenza vaccination in the past as her father died from GB syndrome after receiving influenza vaccine. Review of systems was negative for sore throat, dyspnea, gross hematuria, arthralgias or rash. On physical examination, her blood pressure was elevated at 220/100 mm Hg and there was 3+ pitting edema of the lower extremities. She was afebrile in the ER. The rest of the examination was unremarkable. At the time of ER presentation, the serum creatinine was elevated at 9.93 mg/dL and blood urea nitrogen was 77 mg/dL. The serum creatinine checked three months before presentation to the ER was 0.9 mg/dL. The serum total protein was 7.8 g/dL and serum albumin was low (2.3 g/dL). Because of the high globulin fraction, serum immunofixation was performed, which revealed polyclonal gammopathy but no monoclonal immunoglobulin was seen. Repeat laboratory testing performed subsequently revealed a total protein level of 4.5 g/dL and serum albumin of 2.2 g/dL. Aspartate aminotransferase was mildly elevated (49 U/L). Other liver enzymes were within normal limits. Complete blood count was normal. Urinalysis was significant for 20-30 WBC/hpf, 10-20 RBC/hpf and 3+ proteinuria. Her random urine total protein to creatinine (TP/CR) ratio was significantly elevated at 22. A 24-h urine collection revealed 20.5 g of protein. A non-contrast computed tomography (CT) scan of the abdomen and pelvis in the ER revealed no hydronephrosis or peri-nephric inflammatory changes. Chest X-ray was normal. Workup for secondary causes of the NS and AKI revealed non-reactive hepatitis C virus antibody and hepatitis B surface antigen. The antinuclear antibody, anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA), cryoglobulins, anti-glomerular basement membrane antibody and human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) antibody were all negative. The serum complement levels were normal. A CT scan-guided kidney biopsy was subsequently performed. Kidney biopsy findings: Eight glomeruli were identified on light microscopic examination of the kidney biopsy specimen. The glomeruli showed patent capillary loops and urinary spaces. The interstitium showed patchy edema and mild to moderate inflammatory cell infiltrate composed of mononuclear cells with many eosinophils. The arteries showed mild intimal sclerosis without vasculitis. Immunofluorescence showed scattered fine granular staining for IgG, C3, kappa and lambda light chains in the outer aspect of the glomerular capillary wall. Electron microscopy showed scattered electron dense deposits in the subepithelial and intramembranous locations. Extensive effacement of the epithelial cell foot processes was seen. The kidney biopsy findings were consistent with (stage 1) MN and AIN. Clinical follow-up: The patient was initially started on furosemide and metolazone for management of edema. She was also started on amlodipine and clonidine for management of hypertension. The BP was well controlled with the above medications. She was responding well to the diuretic therapy and had no uremic symptoms, she was not dialyzed. After reviewing the results of the kidney biopsy, the patient was initiated on daily oral prednisone (0.75 mg/kg) with tapering doses over the next 2.5 months. The serum creatinine normalized (1.04 mg/dL) five weeks after initiation of oral prednisone. The serum albumin normalized (3.7 g/dL) after seven weeks, while spot urine TP/CR decreased dramatically to 1.3 after nine weeks of oral corticosteroid therapy. However, one week after completion of prednisone therapy, the patient presented to the office with bilateral lower extremity swelling and 30 pounds weight gain. Laboratory tests performed during that office visit revealed a low serum albumin level of 2.1 g/dL and an elevated serum creatinine level of 2.3 mg/dL. The total cholesterol (417 mg/dL) and triglyceride (608 mg/ dL) levels were also elevated. Her spot urine TP/CR increased significantly to 28. The patient was hospitalized for management of worsening edema. Repeat kidney biopsy performed during her hospital stay revealed rare subepithelial deposits on electron microscopy with a varied degree of translucency suggestive of resorption of previous deposits. There was no evidence of AIN on repeat kidney biopsy. The patient was reinitiated on daily oral prednisone (0.75 mg/kg) soon after reviewing the biopsy results. Prednisone was gradually tapered over the next four months. Two weeks after reinitiation of corticosteroids, her serum creatinine decreased to the normal range (0.88 mg/dL), her serum albumin increased to 3.5 g/dL and spot urine TP/CR decreased to 2.2. Serum albumin improved further to 4.1 g/dL after one month of oral prednisone therapy. Proteinuria continued to decline and spot urine TP/CR normalized (0.2) two weeks after completion of the second course of oral corticosteroid therapy. Since then, the patient has refused further influenza vaccinations. At the five-year follow-up, our patient continues to remain in complete clinical remission of the NS (spot urine TP/CR of 0.1) with normal renal function (serum creatinine: 0.9 mg/dL). Linked to case: 2016059464 (same reporter). Reporter comments: We present a case of MN and severe AKI following the 2009 H1N1 influenza vaccination. Optimal therapy of influenza vaccine-associated glomerular diseases including MN is unknown. Our patient remains in clinical remission with normal renal function, five years after completion of corticosteroid therapy. Based on our experience, one can consider corticosteroid therapy in patients with MN and AIN following influenza vaccination. However, further studies are required to investigate the exact pathogenesis of influenza vaccine-induced MN. Sender's Comments: Company's evaluation and comment: Seriousness criterion/criteria: Medically significant. Listedness: Unlisted. Assessment according to the CCDS for CSL's H1N1 Influenza Vaccine, nephrotic syndrome and all other events are unlisted except fever, nausea and vomiting which are listed. Company Causality: Possible. There was a plausible temporal relationship of 2 weeks for onset of clinical signs and symptoms consistent with nephrotic syndrome.  No other risk causative or risk factors such as NSAIDS use, diabetes, hypertension, connective tissue disease and or HIV infection. Vasculitis with transient renal involvement is a known adverse event with Influenza vaccination in general including H1N1. In concurrence with the authors, although the exact pathogenesis of MN following influenza vaccination is not known, it is possible for autoimmune mediate damage to have occurred by either auto-antibody and or small circulating immune complex deposition in the glomerular basement membrane  induced as an immunologically mediated vaccination response.

70 y/o female of Asian descent developed a mild, pruritic, hive-like rash on her left arm and leg about 2 days (21 Jan 2021) after receipt of her 2nd BioNTech vaccine (injected in her left arm; no other vaccines given on that day). Patient did not self-treat. Rash continued on 26 Jan when patient was evaluated in Medical Center  ER  described as "3 small wheals located on left upper and lower extremity with excoriations"; she was treated with Benadryl 25 mg orally and the itching decreased and the rash significantly diminished. No other signs or symptoms concerning for allergic reaction. Patient also reports onset of muscle aches, starting within 48 hours of vaccine receipt; also reports onset of fatigue, headache, and feeling hot.  The headache and feeling hot resolved within 72 hours, but fatigue and muscle aches continued. Reports muscles hurt in her arms legs, and chest.  Around 22 Jan, patient began having diffuse joint pain in her extremities. The pain became significantly worse on Sun, 24 Jan. Patient self-treated with Ibuprofen with some relief. By 26 Jan, when patient sought evaluation at ER, she described the joint pain as "unbearable" and rated pain intensity as 9/10. In the ER, patient was afebrile and her exam noted: bilateral hand and wrist swelling (left>right), but no redness or warmth at joints; full ROM, but pain increased with movements. Diagnosed as reactive arthritis and prescribed Tiger Balm and Lidocaine patches, with continued Ibuprofen recommended.  At follow-up appointment with patient's PCM on 29 Jan, she reported continued muscle and joint pains. She reported some relief with topical analgesics and Ibuprofen, but Ibuprofen upset her stomach, so was changed to Celecoxib 200 mg twice daily as needed. Topicals and Benadryl were renewed. (Benadryl helped rash, but patient ran out and had recurrence of pruritic rash.) Muscle pain continued in her extremities. Reported fair control of muscle pain with topical analgesics and Celecoxib. Reported having "muscle spasms" in her hands. Patient reported increased sensitivity  painful sensation when she touched something cold. Reported using a pot holder to hold a cold can of soda to reduce pain.  Joint pain primarily in hands, wrists, shoulders, feet, ankles, and knees. Reported swelling of hands and wrists resolved after about 2 weeks. She also had swelling of her left foot, which resolved. Reported some relief of joint pain with topical analgesics and Celecoxib, but joint pain interfering with sleep. Patient's fatigue continued. Spouse describes as decreased stamina. An example:  they used to go out to do errands over a 2-hour period and it would not impact patient's energy level; now, after 2 hours of minimal-to-moderate activity, patient is exhausted.  Follow-up with PCM on 8 and 18 Mar 2021  rash resolved, but generalized muscle aches and joint pains continue.  No localized joint swelling. Full ROM. Labs ordered (see below)  patient's Rheumatoid Factor was elevated; she is pending a Rheumatology evaluation (appointment on 17 April). No history of recent trauma or injury. No previous history of similar joint pain. No history of arthritis or Rheumatic disease.   Not previously diagnosed with COVID and never tested positive for COVID; was quarantined in 2020 after returning from being on a cruise ship. After 1st COVID vaccine in Dec, she experienced a headache and local redness and tenderness at vaccination site, lasting less than 3 days.

patient was sitting in our lobby following covid vaccination when he reported he felt a little dizzy and thought he may faint, (patient was nervous for the vaccine prior to administration), I sent someone to grab a  ice pack and a bottle of water for him and while they were retrieving the ice pack he started to seize. Once the seizure ended I asked patient if he had a history of seizures, his answer was, "not really". I experienced hip joint and leg pain on my left side at night typically commencing three hours into sleep cycle.  In the first week after the vaccine, the pain was quite sharp and severe in my left hip.  Over time the pain spread further down my leg and was a searing ache.  I did not experience leg or joint pain when awake and up and around.  About four days I awoke having what seemed like one of my sleep cycle panic attacks with the exception that I did not experience mental panic, only very rapid heart beat and high blood pressure and arm tingling.  I took alprazolam as prescribed by my physician.  The symptoms were very slow to abate.  I was concerned I was having a stroke or heart attack but decided it was just a panic attack.  By week four following my first vaccine the leg pain had lessened.  After the second vaccine, the entire scenario above reoccured including  hip and leg pain on my left side.  The pain in my joint was not as sharp but it is severe enough to wake me up.  It occurs at about 3:30 am at night and lasts 2-3 hours.  I had a second panic attack with the same description of symptoms (severe rapid heart beat (153) high blood pressure (can provide exact measure - I recall the upper number was 165 and I typically have normal blood pressure).  Took alpralozam and the cardiac synptoms were slow to abate and in fact resurged even after medication.  I continue to have left-side hip and knee join pain and leg pain in my sleep to this day on the same very regular, predictable schedule and the pain continues to be enough to wake me up and make me very uncomfortable, thereby disrupting my sleep every night.  I have had no further "panic" attacks.  At this time, my left side joint and leg pain is somewhat noticeable during the day but I do not have mobility issues.  Am able to walk, exercise etc. normally.

Instantly after receiving my second dose, I started to experience nausea and vomiting. I had to calm myself by thinking about my breathing to normalize it. After everything was kind of back to normal, I was able to go home. I was not able to drive, so a family member took me home. At home, my daughter stayed with me. I started to have fever and chills and so I went into bed. My daughter is young and she was nervous for me. I received a phone call while in bed and I wasn't able to speak. My throat was killing me and I had a lymph node expanded under my left armpit. I took Tylenol and Advil and I was able to fall asleep. I sweat out the fever while in bed. I was in bed for about 48 hours trying to push through these reactions. The palpitations still happen and they did start back up more noticeably after my booster shot.

The patient has been prescribed valacyclovir hydrochloride (VALTREX), prednisone, and tramadol hydrochloride (TRAMADOL) for the management of her painful and persistent symptoms. First, I had a tight throat and I blamed it on the pollen, next at home potato chips got stuck in my throat, and I was just like 'I am eating too quickly', then at boy scout meeting that evening I couldn't breath and blamed it on my mask (we have to wear masks outside), came home took an expired Benadryl and thought, I will call allergist in the morning for an appointment. Next day woke up, felt fine then around 1pm I was on the toilet and I felt a drop like hitting the bottom on the elevator and I thought I won't be able to get off the toilet, I felt super dizzy and nauseous and I thought I would fall. I seriously don't think I have ever felt worse.  Yelled to husband got on sofa and started calling 'ask a nurse' which was stupid, called 911 and they told me to take epi-pen which I should have known to give myself the whole time! EMT came and I went to ER.  Felt better almost immediately with epic-pen and drip with steroids and Benadryl. Next day went to allergist and felt like I was having another reaction, she gave me some additional meds.  I started on Zyrtec and I didn't like how drowsy I was feeling so on 4/5 I didn't take Zyrtec that night and Tuesday I woke up fine and then around 1pm I thought I was going to die, I called the allergist, they said you should continue taking Zyrtec every night and take one then.  I felt like I was having another allergy attack. I felt so dizzy I couldn't move, I felt like I was going to fall, I threw up. I was still too dizzy to move, called ER, went to ER and started feeling better due to the Zyrtec now in my system.

On 11/19/15, 49 yo F presented to clinic for scheduled appointment. During visit, pt was ordered to receive Flu vaccine (QUADRIVALENT) and Pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine 23-valent (PNEUMOVAX-23). Per immunization records, both injections were administered into pt's left deltoid. The influenza vaccine was Lot #UI505AA, exp: 6/30/2016). The pneumococcal vaccine was Lot #L019835, exp: 3/23/2017). On 11/20, pt called clinic and reported that she had developed a fever and the injection site was erythemic and painful. Pt was advised to hydrate and "control her fever with alternating Tylenol 500 mg and Ibuprofen 400 mg (every 6 hours)". On 11/22, pt called and reported increased pain and erythema. Pt then went to ED for evaluation. Pt was diagnosed with cellulitis and prescribed treatment with cephalexin. On 11/23, pt returned to clinic for evaluation, as the area of erythema had expanded beyond the originally demarcated borders. On exam, pt was afebrile with erythema and warmth of left upper arm. Pt was advised to continue cephalexin, monitor site and notify MD if there is no improvement over next 24-48 hours. Pt was then discharged in stable condition. NOTE: Pt has a history of mixed connective tissue disease for which she takes methotrexate 20 mg PO once weekly. This therapy was held during time of event.
